<hr style="margin-top: 0">

<div class="container">
  <div class="text-center">
    <h1 style="font-size: 48px">What Assembly Does For You</h1>

    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-2 col-md-offset-5">
        <hr>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 style="font-size: 32px; font-weight: lighter">Do what you're best at, let us do the rest.</h2>
    <p class="lead text-muted">Leave the hassles to us. We take care of the nauseating business setup, legal docs, hosting and accounting so that great product ideas can be free form the obstacles that too often kill them before they get off the ground.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
      <div>
        <div style="position: absolute">
          <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok text-success"></span>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-left: 30px">
          <h4>Hosting, Domain, and other starting costs are covered</h4>
          <p>Don’t worry about raising capital, Assembly helps every app get started on Heroku and we’ll even cover the costs until revenue exceeds the expenses. Don’t want to Heroku, we’re working with other providers and your always welcome to use anything else that would help your business and expense it to the product.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <br>

      <div>
        <div style="position: absolute">
          <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok text-success"></span>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-left: 30px">
          <h4>No Accountants required</h4>
          <p>Assembly creates a financial dashboard so you can see how handle the business financials (so you don’t have to). When money comes in, expenses are covered, and you get paid from the proceeds.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <br>

      <div>
        <div style="position: absolute">
          <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok text-success"></span>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-left: 30px">
          <h4>Collect payments using the best tools</h4>
          <p>Our Stripe adapter lets you get all the power of stripe without the hassle of incorporating and setting up company bank accounts. Assembly collects the funds for all the products so it can report them to the community and distribute them to the everyone that built it. Collect revenue other ways? <a href="mailto:assembly@helpful.io">Contact Us</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
      <div>
        <div style="position: absolute">
          <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok text-success"></span>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-left: 30px">
          <h4>Control the finances with a virtual account</h4>
          <p>Each product’s core team (that’s you and whomever you invite) can use income or donated funds to cover any costs they choose.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <br>

      <div>
        <div style="position: absolute">
          <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok text-success"></span>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-left: 30px">
          <h4>Keep your IP</h4>
          <p>All source code is open sourced to the community using the AGPL license. Assembly additionally retains a non-exclusive license so we can collect and distribute revenue on behalf of the contributors.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <br>

      <div>
        <div style="position: absolute">
          <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok text-success"></span>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-left: 30px">
          <h4>Legally, we have you covered</h4>
          <p>Assembly handles the legal stuff (sorry, we don’t support illegal products).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <br>

      <div>
        <div style="position: absolute">
          <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok text-success"></span>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-left: 30px">
          <h4>Protection</h4>
          <p>We manage domain the domain for websites and App Store accounts for mobile apps. This is held in escrow to ensure everyone is fairly rewarded. If a product ever leaves assembly, these assets are then transferred to the owners.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="text-center" style="padding-top: 20px">
    <h2 style="font-size: 32px; font-weight: lighter">Assembly is a collaborator on your product.</h2>
    <p class="lead">For this high level of collaboration, we own 10% of your product.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid" style="background: #fff url(<%= image_url 'section-gradient.png' %>) no-repeat center bottom">
  <div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center" style="font-size: 48px">Smart Questions</h2>

    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-2 col-md-offset-5">
        <hr>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="panel-group" style="padding: 40px 0">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#why-not-just-do-open-source" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  Why not just do open source?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="why-not-just-do-open-source" class="panel-collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>Open source is great, Assembly products are built with OSS. What Assembly lets you do is monetize the products you create.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#what-is-assemblys-fee" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  What is Assembly's fee?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="what-is-assemblys-fee" class="panel-collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>Assembly takes 10% of the revenue after expenses.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#who-pays-for-hosting-the-product" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  Who pays for hosting the product?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="who-pays-for-hosting-the-product" class="panel-collapse collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>In some cases, Assembly will help cover these costs before a product launches. In other cases, members of the community pay for them. In any case, these expenditures will be tracked and reimbursed when the product earns profits.</p>
                <p>Once a product is live and earning revenue, monthly costs are paid before community earnings are distributed.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#who-owns-the-intellectual-property" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  Who owns the intellectual property?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="who-owns-the-intellectual-property" class="panel-collapse collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>You do. However, all products on Assembly are licensed under AGPL, and by agreeing to our terms of service you also are granting non-exclusive rights to Assembly to monetize this IP on behalf of the community (and you).</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
        <div class="clearfix visible-xs-block" style="padding-top: 15px"></div>
        <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#can-an-existing-product-be-moved-to-assembly" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  Can an existing product be moved to Assembly?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="can-an-existing-product-be-moved-to-assembly" class="panel-collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>Yes. Usually in this case, we'll "pre-allocate" a fair number of coins to you (and anyone else who built the product with you). It will work similarly to a new product being built on Assembly, but you'll be a diluted at a slower rate. If you have more questions about this, reach out to <a href="mailto:chris@assembly.com">chris@assembly.com</a></p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#can-a-product-leave-assembly" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  Can a product leave Assembly?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="can-a-product-leave-assembly" class="panel-collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>No. An important part of Assembly is that anyone can come help build any product, with full trust that their work (if accepted) will be rewarded with an ownership stake in that product that will translate to a portion of any future revenue.</p>
                <p>In order for Assembly to ensure that the community's work is rewarded in perpetuity, products being built on Assembly need to stay on Assembly.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#can-a-product-be-sold" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  Can a product be sold?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="can-a-product-be-sold" class="panel-collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>Yes. If a third-party offers to acquire an Assembly product and the partners (everyone with ownership stake) decide it is the right decision for the community, the customers and the product, then a product can be sold.</p>
                <p>When a product is sold, earnings are treated like any other revenue and are paid out to the community.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-subtle">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <p class="panel-title">
                <a href="#is-assembly-legal" data-toggle="collapse" style="display: block">
                  <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down small pull-right" style="margin-top: 5px"></span>
                  Is Assembly legal?
                </a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div id="is-assembly-legal" class="panel-collapse collapse">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p>Yes, of course. We've worked hard to figure out the legal challenges of letting people build businesses in this new way.</p>
                <p>Each product on Assembly is legally structured as a partnership, where all stakeholders are partners. The product's profits are paid out to partners as royalties, based on each partner's App Coin ownership.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-large" style="padding: 30px; font-size: 24px">
      <a href="<%= start_idea_path %>" class="btn btn-success btn-lg pull-right">Learn More</a>
      Already have a product and want to migrate it to Assembly?
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<hr style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">

<div class="container">
  <div class="footer" style="border-top: none; margin-top: 0">
    <%= render 'shared/footer_nav' %>
  </div>
</div>
